<div id="review_3832672713" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3832672713" />
    <a title="Fergus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70395042-fergus"><img alt="Fergus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624317933p2/70395042.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3832672713?book_show_action=true">Feb 11, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fergus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fergus" href="/user/show/70395042-fergus">Fergus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3832672713" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15382131883288489629">Fran√ßois Rabelais fired a twenty-four gun cannonade in order to welcome this scatological chef d‚Äô≈ìuvre to one of the bloodiest centuries this side of Hades. The century of the Reformation.<br/><br/>The twenty-four cannons, of course, were the choicest epithets and obscene appellations he could think of for the rioting Protestant factions‚Äô view of those soi-disant damned Catholic clerics. And they‚Äôre scattered abundantly throughout these books.<br/><br/>Cannon fodder indeed.<br/><br/>Our age naturally would never stoop so low</span>
  <span id="freeText15382131883288489629" style="display:none">Fran√ßois Rabelais fired a twenty-four gun cannonade in order to welcome this scatological chef d‚Äô≈ìuvre to one of the bloodiest centuries this side of Hades. The century of the Reformation.<br /><br />The twenty-four cannons, of course, were the choicest epithets and obscene appellations he could think of for the rioting Protestant factions‚Äô view of those soi-disant damned Catholic clerics. And they‚Äôre scattered abundantly throughout these books.<br /><br />Cannon fodder indeed.<br /><br />Our age naturally would never stoop so low, though our recent political history shows us that extremism never sleeps. And even though our wars are largely waged by trade or by proxy, our guilt never sleeps either.<br /><br />None of us can be so over-the-top nowadays with our tinderbox politics, and not get stung.<br /><br />But Rabelais was way, way outta bounds. <br /><br />And would have been appropriately labelled as such, had not Mr Gutenberg enabled every Protestant foot soldier to be equipped with a copy of this book in his backpack allowance.<br /><br />In the same way Bunyan‚Äôs Puritan fantasies battle-readied many an English Roundhead.<br /><br />But Rabelais? <br /><br />In an age like I grew up in (the fifties) his books would have been simply labelled obscene by the Supreme Court and any public reference thereto would have been considered anarchistic rabble-rousing.<br /><br />I know, I know, Rabelais is great literature!<br /><br />But when Henry Miller‚Äôs novels began to appear in the sixties (put it down to JFK‚Äôs cultural glasnost) my mom STILL wouldn‚Äôt hear of us reading him. A little knowledge is a dangerous thing.<br /><br />Unless it brings you back to an awareness of your own, and God‚Äôs, true nature.<br /><br />Yes, my Mom distrusted political hypocrisy of ALL stripes...<br /><br />For which I simply say to her memory now: thank God and all His saints!</span>
  <a data-text-id="15382131883288489629" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
